A realistic stack, flask plus postgres plus redis.

Let us bring everything together with the same flask app from notebook two, now wired to a postgres for storage and a redis for caching. The compose file pins a project name and defines three services. The database uses a postgres image with its user, password, and database name, where the password comes from a required substitution so the stack refuses to start without it, mounts a named volume, has a healthcheck that probes readiness, and restarts unless stopped. The cache uses a redis image with its own named volume, a ping healthcheck, and the same restart policy. And the web service builds from the project, publishes its port bound to local-host only, sets its database and cache connection strings, depends on both the database and the cache being healthy, and also restarts unless stopped. A gitignored dot env file supplies the database password.

It is worth naming what this stack gets right, because each choice fixes a common failure. The database password is required, so there are no accidental empty-password deploys. The web service waits for both dependencies to be healthy, so there are no flaky startup races. The port is bound to local-host, so the app is not accidentally exposed on the host's external interface. Every service restarts, so a crash recovers automatically and survives daemon restarts. The volumes are named, so data persists across down and up, and only the volumes flag wipes it. And the project name is pinned, so there are no collisions with other checkouts.

The day-to-day commands are the ones we have already met, bringing the stack up, checking status including health, tailing one service's logs, dropping into a container or the database with exec, running a one-shot migration with run, and updating images with pull followed by a fresh bring-up. This shape, a declarative stack with healthchecked dependencies, named volumes, local-host-bound ports, and a restart policy on everything, is what a compose-based local dev or single-host deploy should look like today.
